The paper deals with the analysis of concurrent programs, specifically those that use message-passing concurrency in the Go programming language. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) or Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-categories. The use of vector clocks to establish a happens-before relation also suggests that the paper could belong to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also discusses identifying bugs and performance bottlenecks, which could fall under the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. Finally, the paper describes a two-phase method for deriving vector clock information, which could be considered a form of optimization or algorithm design, potentially fitting under the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category.
